1
00:00:02,730 --> 00:00:09,784
Foundation Course 1, Talk 10, The Fourth Noble Truth, Mental Development, Samadhi.

2
00:00:11,788 --> 00:00:20,765
The Fourth Noble Truth, which is the Noble Eightfold Path that leads to the liberation from all suffering, is divided into Morality, Mental Development and Wisdom.

3
00:00:22,027 --> 00:00:26,274
However, this isn't meant to be a progressive list, but a threefold development.

4
00:00:26,609 --> 00:00:40,176
So while we are protecting ourselves from doing harm and keeping as best we can the moral precepts as codified in the five training rules, and while we are also developing the perfections, we need to develop our mental faculties and wisdom.

5
00:00:40,978 --> 00:00:44,786
And the one powerful practice to achieve this is the practice of meditation.

6
00:00:46,284 --> 00:00:50,171
Meditation in the Buddha's practice holds the central place of the middle way.

7
00:00:50,753 --> 00:00:52,655
Its importance lies in two fields.

8
00:00:53,317 --> 00:01:04,656
The first is the purification of the mind, the last of the three primary precepts, the first two, to cease from harm and to do good, being covered by the morality division.

9
00:01:04,676 --> 00:01:08,563
The second is the realization of the supramundane truth, nibbana.

10
00:01:10,147 --> 00:01:17,034
Both of purification of the mind and the enlightenment also include the third division of the Eightfold Path, Wisdom.

11
00:01:17,594 --> 00:01:24,721
But here we are concerned with how to develop the mind so that it can make the necessary insight into itself and into Nirvana.

12
00:01:27,024 --> 00:01:31,448
There are three factors of the Noble Eightfold Path that go to make up this division.

13
00:01:32,069 --> 00:01:35,832
Right effort, right concentration and right awareness.

14
00:01:36,893 --> 00:01:42,319
and there are two areas of life where they are applicable, in meditation practice and in daily life.

15
00:01:43,739 --> 00:01:47,825
The practice and art of meditation in daily life is dealt with elsewhere.

16
00:01:48,245 --> 00:01:52,769
Here we shall investigate the meditative process to see how and why it works.

17
00:01:55,013 --> 00:01:59,998
The first thing we do when we begin to meditate is to take up a sitting posture and sit still.

18
00:02:00,552 --> 00:02:07,319
For most of us this will be the first time we ever sat still in one position without moving for any length of time.

19
00:02:08,781 --> 00:02:15,187
Even when we are engrossed in a film or a TV program, quite unconsciously we are moving and shifting about all the time.

20
00:02:16,248 --> 00:02:24,237
In the practice of meditation all that has to stop and we have to make a resolution not to move for a given period of time.

21
00:02:25,879 --> 00:02:30,205
We start with 20 minutes but we ought to build up to close on an hour as possible.

22
00:02:30,961 --> 00:02:33,625
The actual posture itself is not all that important.

23
00:02:34,306 --> 00:02:39,954
You can meditate sitting on a chair, but the cross-leg posture is worth developing for its future benefit.

24
00:02:40,775 --> 00:02:50,770
Believe it or not, when the legs have settled on the floor, it is a most comfortable position, and more important, gives us a sense of balance, steadiness and groundedness.

25
00:02:52,352 --> 00:02:58,520
It's always a bit of a shock if you've fallen asleep for a moment while sitting on a chair, to suddenly find yourself sprawled on the floor.

26
00:02:59,632 --> 00:03:05,019
However, although comfort and good posture are important, it is the state of mind that carries more weight.

27
00:03:05,819 --> 00:03:09,525
The mind must be alert and this is expressed in the body through the spine.

28
00:03:10,485 --> 00:03:15,050
If the spine is not held with energy, the body sags and pain can result in the back.

29
00:03:15,893 --> 00:03:19,537
If there's too much energy, pain also arises, usually in the neck.

30
00:03:20,878 --> 00:03:24,963
The spine must be held erect and alert with the head balanced gently on the top.

31
00:03:25,956 --> 00:03:30,401
Finally the hands are placed on the lap, one on the other or apart, it doesn't matter.

32
00:03:32,223 --> 00:03:35,508
This is right effort then when it comes to the sitting posture.

33
00:03:36,188 --> 00:03:39,032
Comfortable, still and energised.

34
00:03:41,215 --> 00:03:44,979
The second thing we notice when we first meditate is the silence we sit in.

35
00:03:46,140 --> 00:03:47,481
Some experience it as peace.

36
00:03:48,704 --> 00:03:50,925
All interpersonal interaction is stopped.

37
00:03:51,467 --> 00:03:52,949
We don't communicate with anyone.

38
00:03:53,649 --> 00:03:55,812
No one tries to communicate with us.

39
00:03:56,062 --> 00:03:59,507
The outer person, the one whom everyone knows, is shut down.

40
00:04:00,608 --> 00:04:07,358
This allows us to build up the concentration and sets up the conditions whereby we can observe and get to know the inner person.

41
00:04:10,342 --> 00:04:16,050
In order to build up the concentration we use an object which is obvious to us and so can draw the attention.

42
00:04:17,312 --> 00:04:25,343
Most people find it's not all that difficult to keep the body still for some time but when it comes to the mind it's a very different kettle of fish.

43
00:04:25,795 --> 00:04:30,721
In fact, most meditators comment on how surprised they are to find that the mind is so unruly.

44
00:04:31,764 --> 00:04:34,608
The Buddha described it like a monkey jumping from branch to branch.

45
00:04:36,911 --> 00:04:42,098
Now the object we choose is the breath, just that simple action of breathing in and breathing out.

46
00:04:42,939 --> 00:04:46,605
We don't interfere with it, we just allow the body to breathe.

47
00:04:47,024 --> 00:04:53,452
Some watch the breath coming in and out of the nostrils, others the rising and falling of the stomach.

48
00:04:53,473 --> 00:04:56,497
We should choose the one that seems most obvious to us and stick to it.

49
00:04:57,137 --> 00:05:06,209
There's no special merit attached to either, for the purpose of watching the process of breath is to train the mind to be still, concentrated and alert.

50
00:05:09,834 --> 00:05:13,098
So now we have right effort and right concentration.

51
00:05:13,264 --> 00:05:18,331
right effort here is to put in the energy needed to keep the mind steady on the breath.

52
00:05:19,312 --> 00:05:25,060
If this energy is used for any other purpose then it will begin to undermine the third factor, right awareness.

53
00:05:26,581 --> 00:05:36,454
If we concentrate on the breath to achieve something or to discover something then we are beginning to direct the mind putting ideas and concepts in the way of pure awareness.

54
00:05:37,598 --> 00:05:43,584
we need to develop a very different sort of mind to the one our education system tries to develop.

55
00:05:45,086 --> 00:05:52,314
If we consider our educational system for a moment, we see it is firstly about the mind storing information and learning skills.

56
00:05:53,314 --> 00:06:02,425
Secondly, when once this has been achieved, it is about teaching that trained mind to express ideas and feelings through writing, art, music, science and so on.

57
00:06:03,416 --> 00:06:11,726
But the meditation the Buddha would have us practice is about training the mind to observe itself, to see itself as it really is.

58
00:06:12,447 --> 00:06:15,791
That's what we mean by the word vipassana.

59
00:06:15,812 --> 00:06:18,314
It means literally really or truly seeing.

60
00:06:19,216 --> 00:06:22,740
We become the objective observer of our own minds.

61
00:06:25,584 --> 00:06:31,011
To achieve this we need to consider how a scientist comes to know the world in an objective way.

62
00:06:31,226 --> 00:06:36,932
Suppose she's an ornithologist studying the habits of the common dreadful warbler.

63
00:06:36,952 --> 00:06:38,995
Does she ride on the back of the warbler?

64
00:06:39,014 --> 00:06:39,555
Of course not.

65
00:06:40,456 --> 00:06:42,418
Does she in any way interfere with the warbler?

66
00:06:42,899 --> 00:06:43,139
No.

67
00:06:44,021 --> 00:06:48,565
To do so would be to distort the behaviour of the bird, interfere with its natural habits.

68
00:06:49,586 --> 00:06:55,512
To do so would not be to observe the dreadful warbler as it really is, but as it is interfered with.

69
00:06:56,523 --> 00:07:03,930
If we want to observe the mind as it really is, we must take up a position within ourselves that won't interfere with the workings of the mind.

70
00:07:05,750 --> 00:07:07,872
The mind will offer us no end of entertainment.

71
00:07:08,733 --> 00:07:12,317
It is full of imaginative plots, daydreams, dialogues and emotions.

72
00:07:13,478 --> 00:07:16,281
Before we meditated, we used to indulge in such things.

73
00:07:16,821 --> 00:07:20,985
We'd sit on the bus or drive the car and allow the mind to wander off to sunny beaches.

74
00:07:21,846 --> 00:07:25,668
We'd lie in bed and conjure up plans on how to get more money or win promotion.

75
00:07:26,475 --> 00:07:31,281
we wouldn't be able to sleep for the agitation in the mind, chewing over the day's traumas and tribulations.

76
00:07:32,141 --> 00:07:39,370
But since we've begun meditating, we've pulled away from these habits because we've discovered them to be unwholesome and actually harmful.

77
00:07:41,572 --> 00:07:45,536
This is not to say that there's not a place for constructive fantasy and directed thinking.

78
00:07:46,576 --> 00:07:55,706
What is unwholesome is when our minds indulge in escapist fantasy and thought that develop unskillful negative states of mind such as lust and grudge.

79
00:07:56,918 --> 00:08:10,459
There's a world of difference between using our imagination to think about how we will gather the money together and organize our trip to the Costa del Sol, and fantasizing for three or four hours, wandering up and down beaches, attracting the opposite sex.

80
00:08:12,362 --> 00:08:21,576
Allowing the depressed mind to construct a fantasy-fabricated world as a totally depressing and despairing place is a very different...

81
00:08:21,708 --> 00:08:27,036
thing from trying to solve real problems in our relationships and at work which may be depressing us.

82
00:08:28,898 --> 00:08:37,551
But in meditation practice we do not indulge in either, neither the constructive skillful use of the mind nor the destructive unskillful use of the mind.

83
00:08:38,993 --> 00:08:41,797
In meditation we are trying to observe the mind as it is.

84
00:08:43,018 --> 00:08:49,167
When we are indulging in any kind of fantasy or thinking we are riding on the back of the common dreadful warbler.

85
00:08:49,855 --> 00:08:54,038
If we keep doing this, we'll never come to know what the mind really is.

86
00:08:56,741 --> 00:08:59,024
There are many things in our minds that cause us suffering.

87
00:08:59,764 --> 00:09:05,750
Old memories, present problems, negative emotions and moods that we prefer not to look at, not to acknowledge.

88
00:09:07,173 --> 00:09:10,275
Usually, when something negative comes up, we tend to want to escape.

89
00:09:10,996 --> 00:09:13,259
If we feel bored, for instance, we'll turn the TV on.

90
00:09:14,139 --> 00:09:16,302
If we feel lonely, we'll call a friend or get drunk.

91
00:09:17,277 --> 00:09:23,345
If we get angry with someone we're not supposed to, we'll swallow it, anything but to feel the painful states of mind in us.

92
00:09:24,787 --> 00:09:30,073
All these strategies and tactics we employ to escape this suffering in the mind are all repressive measures.

93
00:09:30,674 --> 00:09:32,076
They work in a very subtle way.

94
00:09:32,697 --> 00:09:36,283
They push these unwanted feelings and thoughts back into the subconscious.

95
00:09:37,264 --> 00:09:40,347
This is like putting the rare dreadful wobbler into a cage.

96
00:09:41,154 --> 00:09:44,039
We might like to see it there, it's pretty, but it's not natural.

97
00:09:44,421 --> 00:09:45,943
It's not how the warbler really is.

98
00:09:46,504 --> 00:09:48,828
Its natural habits are not allowed free expression.

99
00:09:49,610 --> 00:09:52,615
It will find other ways of behaving which are unnatural to it.

100
00:09:53,157 --> 00:10:01,392
In time, the warbler may sicken and die, so unused is it to confinement, or its behaviour will become strange for its species, neurotic.

101
00:10:02,671 --> 00:10:16,335
Just as our ornithologist will get a distorted view of the bird by studying it in a false situation, so we will get a very distorted view of ourselves if a great part of us is unseen, unknown, buried deep in the subconscious.

102
00:10:19,078 --> 00:10:25,269
Right awareness is to be able to see the mind as it really is, as it displays itself to us.

103
00:10:26,717 --> 00:10:33,306
When meditators first practice Vipassana meditation, they're often surprised to find how much suffering there is in the mind.

104
00:10:34,567 --> 00:10:37,910
I knew I had anger in me, but this anger that's coming up is frightening.

105
00:10:38,652 --> 00:10:42,755
I knew I was depressed, but I didn't think I was this depressed.

106
00:10:43,476 --> 00:10:45,620
I know I'm an anxious type, but this is terrifying.

107
00:10:47,381 --> 00:10:56,251
Sometimes it unfortunately happens that the meditator blames the meditation, but in reality all that's happening is that the lid is being taken off, the dustbin,

108
00:10:57,514 --> 00:11:01,741
All our lives we've trained ourselves to bottle up, to can our feelings.

109
00:11:03,225 --> 00:11:17,649
As soon as we meditate, all the repressive ploys and tricks are suddenly taken away and out of the subconscious there arises a welter of unresolved guilts, angers, frustrations, sorrows, depressions, anxieties, fears, you name it, you'll find it.

110
00:11:20,076 --> 00:11:31,152
A great deal of our meditation practice is to allow these painful feelings to surface into awareness and to observe them, to feel them, to really feel them as they really are.

111
00:11:32,734 --> 00:11:34,517
Now we can see why we must sit still.

112
00:11:35,398 --> 00:11:40,985
When these feelings, emotions, moods come up, our reactions have always been to escape, to run away.

113
00:11:41,567 --> 00:11:44,750
But now our bodies are still, there's nowhere to go.

114
00:11:45,607 --> 00:11:48,932
There is no way in which these negative states can now be avoided.

115
00:11:49,413 --> 00:11:52,456
Indeed, as meditators we don't want to avoid them anymore.

116
00:11:53,157 --> 00:12:00,086
We've come to a point in our lives when we've decided to sort things out, to get the mind straight, to purify the mind.

117
00:12:02,869 --> 00:12:08,235
In order to realize how it works, we need to remind ourselves how these mental states were created in the first place.

118
00:12:09,597 --> 00:12:14,703
The Buddha taught, it is our desire and our will that play a crucial role.

119
00:12:14,836 --> 00:12:18,464
Desire, with its corollary, aversion, creates the motivation.

120
00:12:19,004 --> 00:12:23,735
The will activates it, orders the mind to develop it, and hence a state of mind is produced.

121
00:12:25,158 --> 00:12:32,052
All our lives we've indulged our likes and dislikes and felt frustrated or depressed when we've not got what we wanted.

122
00:12:32,807 --> 00:12:35,831
When we have what we want, we're afraid to lose it.

123
00:12:36,611 --> 00:12:45,562
It's not so bad if it's a watch or a book, but if it's my job or a relationship, my moods, emotions, states of mind can be very painful indeed.

124
00:12:47,544 --> 00:12:55,173
When we meditate, in the light of awareness, all these negative states arise, but we don't indulge them and we don't push them away.

125
00:12:55,953 --> 00:12:57,515
So what happens to these mental states?

126
00:12:58,317 --> 00:13:01,701
They die away, they lose energy, they fade out.

127
00:13:02,238 --> 00:13:04,881
The Buddha's description of the process was of a fire.

128
00:13:05,823 --> 00:13:08,687
Throwing logs on a fire will not press it out.

129
00:13:09,028 --> 00:13:10,150
They create a bonfire.

130
00:13:10,490 --> 00:13:11,332
This is repression.

131
00:13:12,433 --> 00:13:15,960
We can't draw the energy out of the fire by throwing sawdust on it.

132
00:13:16,922 --> 00:13:19,566
This only makes the fire flare up.

133
00:13:19,586 --> 00:13:25,274
If we want the fire to die out, we simply leave it alone and let it burn itself out.

134
00:13:26,234 --> 00:13:27,755
It's the same with our negativities.

135
00:13:28,375 --> 00:13:35,283
Just watching, just observing everything that comes into the mind, allows it to spend its energy and exhaust itself.

136
00:13:35,724 --> 00:13:38,086
It simply fades out, dies away.

137
00:13:40,447 --> 00:13:47,294
But more, this watching is not just a passive activity, allowing this to burn out before our very eyes, as it were.

138
00:13:47,635 --> 00:13:54,822
It is also active in that the attention is directed to a particular quality of all that arises into the awareness.

139
00:13:56,102 --> 00:13:59,568
That quality is the characteristic of transiency, of change.

140
00:14:00,792 --> 00:14:10,590
It is at this point that Vipassana meditation moves from being a psychotherapy, a way of healing and purifying the mind and heart, to a spiritual practice.

141
00:14:10,610 --> 00:14:17,503
Hereby spiritual practice is meant the discovery of what lies beyond this apparent realism of our body and mind.

142
00:14:18,023 --> 00:14:29,336
For as we observe the arising and passing nature of our breath, our thoughts, our emotions and our sensations, we slowly begin to experience ourselves more and more the objective observer.

143
00:14:31,118 --> 00:14:40,048
A distance is created between the objects of our awareness and the awareness itself, which grows wider and wider and more and more distinct in its separateness.

144
00:14:41,107 --> 00:14:47,278
As this distance grows, so does our identity, our self-definition, our egos grow dimmer and dimmer.

145
00:14:48,019 --> 00:14:57,756
For we realize that everything we are experiencing, which we once took to be some sort of permanent and substantial personality, is but a mass of passing phenomena.

146
00:14:58,938 --> 00:15:01,302
There comes a time when even the observer vanishes.

147
00:15:03,186 --> 00:15:05,509
For instance, pain might arise in the knees.

148
00:15:05,931 --> 00:15:06,812
In fact, it will.

149
00:15:07,804 --> 00:15:18,197
We put all our effort into keeping the attention centered on the sensations, so that our concentration grows narrower and narrower, until we are aware of only a very small area.

150
00:15:19,278 --> 00:15:29,490
There comes a time when we are aware of just sensations arising and passing away at very fast speeds, and although we once perceived them as unpleasant, we do not do so now.

151
00:15:30,191 --> 00:15:34,976
We experience them as just pure sensation, just arising and passing away.

152
00:15:36,239 --> 00:15:46,630
After such an experience we might also reflect, we might also realize by our own personal experience, that the consciousness of these sensations was separate from the actual sensations themselves.

153
00:15:47,350 --> 00:15:50,394
In fact, the consciousness was not the sensations.

154
00:15:50,956 --> 00:15:53,719
Consciousness is one thing, sensations another.

155
00:15:55,980 --> 00:16:00,306
The human mind, just like the human body, is made up of parts.

156
00:16:00,606 --> 00:16:12,456
This is beginning to experience what is known in Buddhism as anatta, that teaching particular to the Buddha that no permanent soul or self or substantial entity is to be found in the body and mind.

157
00:16:13,533 --> 00:16:18,322
This insubstantiality is another of the basic characteristics of our existence.

158
00:16:19,264 --> 00:16:25,077
And because everything is transient and insubstantial, no everlasting happiness can be found there either.

159
00:16:26,059 --> 00:16:34,157
In this way, we come to realize for ourselves the essential unsatisfactoriness of the human condition, the third characteristic, dukkha.

160
00:16:35,369 --> 00:16:44,485
So it is that by observing the phenomena of the mind from the point of view of the characteristic of transiency of change that the nirvanic experience can be had.

161
00:16:45,746 --> 00:16:55,605
For upon the observation of this characteristic of transiency, the other two characteristics become more obvious, unsatisfactoriness and insubstantiality.

162
00:16:56,648 --> 00:17:15,233
As these characteristics become more and more obvious, and as the concentration and awareness become more and more fine, more penetrating, the intuitive faculty that realizes all these things intuits nibbana, that which is beyond all these changing, unsatisfactory and insubstantial phenomena.

163
00:17:16,316 --> 00:17:19,339
This the Buddha put clearly in three famous verses.

164
00:17:21,083 --> 00:17:23,465
All that is conditioned is transient.

165
00:17:24,407 --> 00:17:27,371
When one sees this with wisdom, one tires of suffering.

166
00:17:28,192 --> 00:17:29,874
This is the path of purification.

167
00:17:31,276 --> 00:17:33,518
All that is conditioned is unsatisfying.

168
00:17:33,999 --> 00:17:37,603
When one sees this with wisdom, then one tires of suffering.

169
00:17:38,284 --> 00:17:40,046
This is the path of purification.

170
00:17:41,326 --> 00:17:43,390
Everything is insubstantial.

171
00:17:44,049 --> 00:17:47,413
When one sees this with wisdom, then one tires of suffering.

172
00:17:48,295 --> 00:17:50,617
This is the path of purification.

173
00:17:52,875 --> 00:17:55,820
Now the whole of this meditation process rests upon faith.

174
00:17:56,742 --> 00:17:58,165
Faith here does not mean belief.

175
00:17:59,688 --> 00:18:03,996
The Buddha was quite clear in all his teachings that he didn't want blind belief.

176
00:18:05,318 --> 00:18:13,212
Belief can be understood here as uncritically accepting statements about something that have not or cannot be proven.

177
00:18:14,594 --> 00:18:21,325
The Buddha states there is nibbana, an end to suffering, which is not annihilation, that transcends the experience of body and mind.

178
00:18:22,266 --> 00:18:24,490
But he never describes it, save in the negative.

179
00:18:25,711 --> 00:18:29,978
It is the unborn, the unbecoming, the uncreated, and the uncompounded.

180
00:18:31,119 --> 00:18:39,133
He doesn't ask us to believe this, but he does ask us to put trust, to have faith in him, to give him the benefit of the doubt.

181
00:18:39,416 --> 00:18:43,844
Unless we can do this, all our efforts at concentration will be undermined.

182
00:18:44,785 --> 00:18:51,315
All the time we'll be wondering and questioning and doubting, all precious energy wasted, unreclaimable, lost forever.

183
00:18:51,815 --> 00:18:52,516
And what's the point?

184
00:18:53,336 --> 00:19:01,368
The Buddha is only asking us to try and see if it works for us, just as a doctor offers us medicine on the understanding we trust the medication.

185
00:19:03,972 --> 00:19:07,298
So with trust, effort and interest are aroused.

186
00:19:08,037 --> 00:19:14,247
With these, our concentration is that much easier to achieve, and with it, awareness comes easily.

187
00:19:15,429 --> 00:19:22,039
Within this watchful and alert awareness, the faculty of intuition, that which makes insight, lies potential.

188
00:19:23,142 --> 00:19:29,471
When these spiritual faculties are balanced and highly enough developed, vipassana insight actualizes.

189
00:19:31,527 --> 00:19:35,271
Whenever we sit in this way, we can presume that two things are happening.

190
00:19:35,833 --> 00:19:43,061
Firstly, that there is a healing process of the mind and heart, allowing all the negativities to arise and pass away.

191
00:19:44,002 --> 00:19:47,488
This fulfills the third primary precept to purify the mind.

192
00:19:48,950 --> 00:19:58,142
And secondly, that the spiritual faculties of faith, effort, concentration, awareness and intuitive wisdom are being developed.

193
00:19:58,560 --> 00:20:14,780
Given constant practice, the meditator is bound to succeed in achieving a happier and more peaceful life, and is all the time laying the foundations for the eventual experience of insight knowledge into the ultimate, that liberation from suffering, nibbana.

194
00:20:15,662 --> 00:20:16,844
There's no doubt about this.

195
